<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-472-688  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 472 688.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  July 24 1989 v8 n15 p73(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>House bills attach penalties to abuse.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Furcron, Wyckliffe.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesSecurityLegal IssuesComputer CrimesLaw EnforcementLegislation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>House Bills Attach Penalties to AbuseandM;Under criminal statutes, prosecuting the creators of computer viruses isdifficult.andP;  Only the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act deals with computer crimes,and it does not specifically cover viruses.andM;From a prosecutor's standpoint, at best only a small portion of a defendant'smisconduct will be punished.andP;  Most of his acts will fall beyond the bounds ofwhat current statutes define as criminal behavior.andM;Some prosecutors would rather not prosecute in view of these technicaldifficulties.andP;  However, two bills are pending before the House ofRepresentative that may go a long way toward rectifying the situation.andM;In July 1988, Rep.andP;  Wally Herger (R-Calif.) introduced HR 5062, the ComputerVirus Eradication Act of 1988, providing criminal penalties and civil relieffor the knowing introduction of a virus or similar program.andP;  The bill died incommittee.andM;In January 1989, Herger introduced the first of two new bills dealing withcomputer viruses.andM;Both bills are pending before the House Judiciary Committee's subcommittee oncrime.andM;HR 55 is similar though not identical to HR 5062.andP;  It would amend theComputer Fraud and Abuse Act to provide criminal penalties for insertinginformation or commands while knowing or having reason to believe they mightcause loss, expense or risk to the health or welfare of the computer, itsusers or anyone who relies on information processed by it.andM;That deals with the major sources of virus exposure: using files from anelectronic bulletin board or sharing files in floppy disks.andM;While the general scope of criminal acts is broad under HR 55, not allcomputer viruses fall within its reach.andP;  There is no crime unless the act wasaffected or furthered by interstate or foreign commerce, as in the ComputerFraud and Abuse Act.andM;Besides criminal penalties, HR 55 authorizes civil actions in which theprevailing party may receive attorney fees and costs of litigation.andM;Rep.andP;  Tom McMilan (D-Md.) introduced the second bill, HR287, which would adda new &quot;sabotage of computer systems&quot; section to the criminal mischiefstatutes.andM;The bill proscribes willfull and knowing sabotage computer hardware orsoftware resulting in loss of data, impaired computer operations or tangibleloss or harm to the computer owner.andP;  Like HR 55, the bill provides forattorney fees and expenses of litigation in addition to civil damages, finesand imprisonment.andM;Although the Senate is not considering any bills on computer viruses, it isstudying the problem.andP;  The Subcommittee on Technology and the Law has heardtestimony from FBI director William Sessions and Clifford Stoll, a HarvardUniversity scientist who tracked down a West German spy who gained access toa Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory network.andM;The General Accounting Office completed a report on computer viruses for theSenate Subcommittee on Telecommunications and Finance.andP;  Both subcommitteesplant to hold more hearings.andO;</TEXT></DOC>